Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @potatoes{600%g} into 2cm chunks (peeling optional). Pop the chunks
onto a large (lined) #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, season with
@salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single
layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}.
Turn the tray halfway through.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Meanwhile, trim the @carrots{2}, then halve lengthways (no need to peel).
Chop into 1cm wide, 5cm long batons. Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and
grated) (or use a garlic press).

Pop the carrot onto a large (lined) baking tray. Toss with garlic, a drizzle of
@oil{to taste}, @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Spread out in a single
layer.

Roast on the middle shelf until tender, ~{20-25%minutes}. Turn the tray halfway
through.

When the potatoes have 15 mins left to cook, place a pan over high heat with a
drizzle of @oil{to taste}. Season the @21 Day Aged Irish Sirloin Steak{250%g}
with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Fry the sirloin until browned, ~{1-2%minutes} each side for medium-rare. Cook
for another ~{1-2%minutes} on each side if you want it more well-done.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Meat is safe to
> eat when the outside is browned.

Once cooked, transfer to a #board{}, cover and allow to rest.

Return the pan to medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}. Once hot,
fry the @Irish Bacon Lardons{100%g} until golden, stirring occasionally,
~{5-7%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Cook lardons
> thoroughly.

Pour the @Red Wine Jus{2%sachets} into the pan with the bacon. Cook, stirring,
until warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}. Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and
@pepper{to taste}.

Thinly slice the steak.

Divide the sliced sirloin between plates. Serve the roasted carrot and potatoes
alongside. Drizzle the sirloin with rich bacon red wine jus.